Rating: 3
We love Moroccan and Indian food-this was yummy. Had rubbed the beef and skewered chunks with red pepper and onion but didnt cook it til a day later. Flavors penetrated the beef, and we only cooked the skewers for a few minutes as we like our beef rare. I would use way less black pepper-overpowered the other spices and I like a grating of cinammon in mine-less sugar. Served with yogurt mint sauce. Yum.

Rating: 4
My family really liked the rub. It is an easy way to cook tenderloin and ensure a crisp crust. I will try some of the other versions in the future, but the cumin flavor is one that we will surely try again.

Rating: 3
The rub is great and very versatile as is. I have never tried it on beef, but it is great on thinly sliced boneless porkloin. Just be careful not to overcook the pork as it will dry out very quickly. I made a banana-orange compote with some sugar and cloves that nicely complimented the sugar-spice rubbed pork.

Rating: 3
I made it as written (the Moroccan version) and was generally very pleased. The result was very flavorful but a bit sweet for my taste. When I make it again, I'll cut back on the sugar.

Rating: 3
Since I didn't like the Moroccan spices and could not find Lavender on the shelf at the supermarket, I substituted and used Rosemary, Sage and Thyme... close enough for Provençal/Mediteranian. It worked fine. Served a Cotes de Rhone wine for a nice herbal match.

Rating: 2
I enjoyed the "Tuscan" version much more than the standard recipe. A nice, easy dish overall.